<body>
<div class="wrap">
  <header>
    <div class="eyebrow">Principles of Microeconomics · Lesson 4</div>
    <h1>Market Efficiency<br/><em>vs</em> Market Failures</h1>
    <div class="sub">Tap any branch to explore</div>
  </header>

  <div class="legend">
    <span class="chip core">Core Concept</span>
    <span class="chip fail">Failure</span>
    <span class="chip fix">Fix / Response</span>
  </div>

  <div class="controls">
    <button class="btn" id="expandAll">Expand all</button>
    <button class="btn" id="collapseAll">Collapse all</button>
  </div>

  <!-- 01 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="core">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">01</span>
      <span class="title">Efficient Markets</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>A market that produces the <strong>maximum output</strong> of desirable goods from given inputs, with maximum consumer and producer satisfaction.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Productive efficiency</strong>Max output, min resource input.</li>
        <li><strong>Allocative efficiency</strong>Producing what consumers actually want.</li>
        <li><strong>Adam Smith's "invisible hand"</strong>Many buyers + sellers, no price-setters, free entry/exit, full price/cost paid, price rations supply &amp; demand.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="key-box">
        <span class="label">Equilibrium</span>
        Quantity supplied = quantity demanded. No surplus, no shortage.
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 02 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="core">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">02</span>
      <span class="title">Pareto Optimality</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Vilfredo Pareto, Italian economist, early 1920s. A system is <em>optimal</em> when no reallocation can make one person better off without making another worse off.</p>
      <p>Using the PPF (Computers vs Clothing): moving from point D to point B is a Pareto improvement — more of both goods, nobody loses. D → A or D → C makes one preference group worse off, so neither is a Pareto improvement.</p>
      <div class="key-box">
        <span class="label">The test</span>
        Can we gain for one without loss to another? If yes, we're not yet optimal.
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 03 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="core">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">03</span>
      <span class="title">Price vs Value</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p><strong>Value</strong> = what you're willing to pay (marginal benefit) or willing to forgo to produce. <strong>Price</strong> = what's actually charged.</p>
      <p>In the $8.50 lunch example: at equilibrium, consumer value = price = producer value. Everyone's marginal benefit equals their marginal cost — that's efficiency.</p>
      <div class="formula">MB = MC</div>
      <p>If <em>MB &gt; MC</em>: produce more (under-production).<br/>If <em>MC &gt; MB</em>: produce less (over-production).</p>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 04 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="core">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">04</span>
      <span class="title">Consumer &amp; Producer Surplus</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p><strong>Consumer surplus</strong> = what consumers would have paid minus what they actually paid.</p>
      <p><strong>Producer surplus</strong> = price received minus the minimum producers would have accepted.</p>
      <div class="key-box">
        <span class="label">Lunch example @ $8.50</span>
        Consumer surplus: $1.00 (from $9.50 buyer) + $0.50 (from $9.00 buyer) = <strong>1.5</strong><br/>
        Producer surplus: $1.00 + $0.50 = <strong>1.5</strong><br/>
        Total surplus = <strong>3.0</strong> — maximum possible.
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 05 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fail">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">05</span>
      <span class="title">Deadweight Loss</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>The lost surplus when a market isn't at equilibrium. Any output level other than where MB = MC creates deadweight inefficiency.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Under-production (MB &gt; MC)</strong>Price too low (e.g., $8.00 lunch). Could gain surplus by producing more.</li>
        <li><strong>Over-production (MC &gt; MB)</strong>Price too high (e.g., $9.00 lunch). Could gain surplus by producing less.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Government <em>price ceilings</em> (rent control) cause under-production. <em>Price floors</em> (minimum wage) cause over-production.</p>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 06 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fail">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">06</span>
      <span class="title">Failure: Monopoly Power</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Little or no competition → higher prices, lower output, MB &gt; MC, deadweight loss for society.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Natural monopoly</strong>Economies of scale make one producer cheapest (e.g., city bus). Government grants sole-supplier status.</li>
        <li><strong>Patents &amp; copyrights</strong>Temporary monopoly to reward innovation, then competition restored.</li>
      </ul>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 07 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fail">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">07</span>
      <span class="title">Failure: Externalities</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Third parties — not part of a transaction — are affected. Price doesn't reflect true social cost or benefit.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Merit goods (positive)</strong>Spillover benefits. Example: public education → employed, productive, less reliant on welfare.</li>
        <li><strong>Demerit goods (negative)</strong>Spillover costs. Example: car pollution affects people who didn't buy the car.</li>
      </ul>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 08 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fail">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">08</span>
      <span class="title">Failure: Moral Hazard</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>One party takes a risk, but someone else bears the cost.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Health</strong>Smoking/drinking — medical costs pushed to insurance pools and public hospitals.</li>
        <li><strong>2007 subprime crisis</strong>Bankers made risky loans for short-term profit; government absorbed losses to prevent macro collapse.</li>
      </ul>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 09 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fail">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">09</span>
      <span class="title">Failure: Public Goods</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Goods with two unusual traits:</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Non-excludable</strong>Can't prevent people from using it.</li>
        <li><strong>Non-rival</strong>One person's use doesn't reduce another's.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Example: a lighthouse. Any ship benefits — no way to bill them. Markets can't price these efficiently, so government typically provides them (defense, public health, security).</p>
      <div class="key-box">
        <span class="label">Free Rider Problem</span>
        Some benefit without paying their share — undermines voluntary funding of public goods.
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 10 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fix">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">10</span>
      <span class="title">Government Fixes</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Goal: <em>internalize</em> the external cost or benefit so the market price reflects true social value.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>For demerit goods</strong>Taxes, regulation, fines (e.g., catalytic converters → lower supply, higher price, less pollution).</li>
        <li><strong>For merit goods</strong>Subsidies to consumers or producers → increase demand or supply → more output.</li>
      </ul>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 11 -->
  <div class="node" data-type="fix">
    <div class="node-head">
      <span class="num">11</span>
      <span class="title">The Intervention Debate</span>
      <span class="toggle">+</span>
    </div>
    <div class="body"><div class="body-inner">
      <p>Should government step in? Economists disagree on extent and means.</p>
      <ul class="sub-list">
        <li><strong>Pro-intervention</strong>When MB &gt; MC at the social level, government action can reduce deadweight loss.</li>
        <li><strong>Coase Theorem &amp; free-market view</strong>Parties can often negotiate solutions themselves (e.g., farmers + beekeepers + consumers). Austrian school, Milton Friedman: intervention adds cost and blocks market self-correction.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="key-box">
        <span class="label">Bottom line</span>
        Public expenditure is justified when marginal social benefit exceeds marginal social cost — but measurement is hard.
      </div>
    </div></div>
  </div>

  <footer>End · Lesson 4</footer>
</div>

<script>
  const nodes = document.querySelectorAll('.node');
  nodes.forEach(n => {
    n.querySelector('.node-head').addEventListener('click', () => {
      n.classList.toggle('open');
    });
  });
  document.getElementById('expandAll').addEventListener('click', () => {
    nodes.forEach(n => n.classList.add('open'));
  });
  document.getElementById('collapseAll').addEventListener('click', () => {
    nodes.forEach(n => n.classList.remove('open'));
  });
</script>
</body>
</html>
